### Describe your problem

Added bge-m3 launched by vllm to OpenAI-API-Compatible via conf/llm_factories.json, but after running bash docker/launch_backend_service.sh, an error occurred when creating a knowledge base using bge-m3@OpenAI-API-Compatible: Unauthorized model: bge-m3@OpenAI-API-Compatible

comment.body:
<!-- Greeting -->
Hi @yangyuren03! I'm [Dosu](https://go.dosu.dev/dosubot) and Iâ€™m helping the ragflow team.

<!-- Answer -->
The "Unauthorized model: bge-m3@OpenAI-API-Compatible" error usually means the model isn't correctly registered under the OpenAI-API-Compatible factory in your conf/llm_factories.json. Make sure you add bge-m3 to the "llm" array for the OpenAI-API-Compatible section, using the right format (including llm_name, model_type, base_url, and an API key placeholder like "no-key-need" if your VLLM server doesn't require authentication). The model name must match exactly what the backend expects. After editing the config, restart your backend service for changes to take effect. Leaving the API key empty or mismatching names will cause this error. If you're running inside Docker, use the host's internal IP for base_url instead of localhost or 127.0.0.1. More details are in [this thread](https://github.com/infiniflow/ragflow/issues/8343#issuecomment-2982827038) and [config example](https://github.com/infiniflow/ragflow/blob/d874683ae4bc3446464fc406a9b4e5da8f78a8a7/conf/llm_factories.json).

# Description

This PR refactors the timeout middleware to properly enforce request timeouts by:

1. Wrapping the handler execution in a goroutine.
2 Using a `select` statement to handle three possible outcomes:

    - Handler completes successfully.
    - Handler panics (panic is propagated).
    - Timeout occurs, triggering cfg.OnTimeout if set, or returning fiber.ErrRequestTimeout..

- The timeout is respected in real time.
- Handlers have the opportunity to observe context cancellation if needed.
- Panics are safely propagated without losing stack traces.

pull_request.title: Update
Make Pow type-agnostic and move it back to numerics
pull_request.body:
This makes the generators in quantities/generators.hpp specific to the definition of operations on Quantity that correspond to predefined operations. When we introduce our own functions that work on Quantity and other things (e.g., `Pow`), we put that in `numerics` (why would `Pow` on a boost multiprecision type live in `quantities`?).

`Exponentiation` works like `Product` and does not know anything about how `Quantity` works (and thus likewise for `Derivatives` etc.).
`Pow` returns an `Exponentiation` and thus does not need to know anything about how `Quantity` works (just like other templatized numerics, e.g., `DoublePrecision`.

The headers that define constants depend on numerics::elementary_functions.

pull_request.title: Feat(paladin) configurable â€œsanctuary vs kingsâ€ policy on tanks + safe targeting
pull_request.body:
Ok Guys tis @/!%** Paladin  is driving me crazy!

### Summary

This PR introduces a configurable policy to prefer Blessing of Sanctuary over Blessing of Kings on tanks, and hardens the casting logic so Kings wonâ€™t overwrite Sanctuary (and vice-versa). 
In WotLK, Sanctuary provides 3% damage reduction and returns resources on avoidance, making it a strong tank blessing; Kings remains a universal fallback. 


### Why

- Many groups want Sanctuary on tanks (mitigation + resource return), Kings for everyone else. Playerbots previously defaulted to Kings in some paths or kept Sanctuary from replacing Kings immediately.
- I also ensure the â€œone Paladin blessing per targetâ€ rule is respected by preventing accidental overwrites. 


### What changed

1. New policy switch

- AiPlayerbot.Paladin.SanctuaryPriority (default 1)

- 1 => Prefer Sanctuary on tanks (if learned), Kings elsewhere.
- 0 => Prefer Kings; the Sanctuary action wonâ€™t auto-apply.

2. Sanctuary action is â€œstrictâ€

- The Sanctuary action never falls back to Kings. If the target isnâ€™t a tank (or the spell isnâ€™t known), it does nothing and lets the Kings action handle the rest.

3. Allow replacement when prioritized

- When SanctuaryPriority=1, the Sanctuary action targets party/raid members missing Sanctuary only, even if they already have Kings, so the tank gets Sanctuary immediately (Kings => Sanctuary upgrade).

4. Kings wonâ€™t overwrite Sanctuary

- The Kings actionâ€™s target filter now excludes Sanctuary (mono + greater), preventing Kings from replacing an already-applied Sanctuary.

5. Main-Tank focus for fast application

- If SanctuaryPriority=1 and the Main Tank lacks Sanctuary, the Sanctuary action forces its target to the MT before casting. This avoids selector ordering issues (master/healer first) and guarantees prompt application to the tank.


### Configuration
```
# Paladin â€” Sanctuary policy on tanks
# 1 = Sanctuary on tanks if learned (fallback Kings)
# 0 = Kings has priority; Sanctuary is not used automatically
# Default: 1
AiPlayerbot.Paladin.SanctuaryPriority = 1
```
Works alongside Strict Role Mode (OFF/ON/AUTO) and Greater/Single upgrade logic; no change required to existing settings.


### Implementation notes:

**Selector changes : **

**Sanctuary GetTargetValue():**

- Priority ON => match  without Sanctuary  (allows replacing Kings).
- Priority OFF => legacy behavior (requires neither Kings nor Sanctuary).

**Kings GetTargetValue() now excludes both Kings and Sanctuary.**

**Decision function**

- GetActualBlessingOfSanctuary(...) returns Sanctuary only for tanks (or the explicit Main Tank), otherwise empty (no cast). No implicit Kings fallback here.

**Execute path**

**Sanctuary Execute(...) optionally retargets the Main Tank if he lacks Sanctuary, then applies normal Greater vs Single upgrade with reagent handling.**


### Acceptance tests

**Default (priority=1)**

**Group with Prot Paladin (bstats), Warrior Prot, others:**

- Everyone receives Kings (Greater when appropriate).
- Warrior Protâ€™s Kings is immediately replaced by Sanctuary.
- Subsequent Kings passes do not overwrite Sanctuary.


**Priority=0**

- Same setup: tanks receive Kings; Sanctuary is not applied automatically.


**No Sanctuary learned**

- Priority=1 or 0: Kings behavior unchanged; no Sanctuary attempts.


### Backward compatibility

- Default is priority=1, which aligns with common WotLK tank buff practice (Sanctuary on tanks; Kings elsewhere). No behavior change for non-tank targets. The change is localized and low-risk.


**Why Sanctuary?**

- Greater Blessing of Sanctuary on WotLK: 3% damage taken reduction; +10% Strength/Stamina; returns mana/rage/runic power on block/parry/dodge. 
- Greater Blessing of Kings (WotLK): +10% stats; only one Paladin blessing per target at a time. 

Thanks for reviewing and tests.
